{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2abbott_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280604604/1945101401/0590.xml":{"full_text":"SAVANNAH'. 'CHARLESTON WILMINGTON WASHINGTON\nTAMP* MIAMI ^\"\u201c7 NEW VORK MEXICO CITY\nSoutheastern Oil\nAND AFFILIATES\nGkaham Building\nJacksonville 2, Fla.\nii uu&vmiciy piwpci ui.v,c:\u00a3ji wim &t?ieiiny me mings\nthat cannot be changed. But by all means let's have, the cour\nage to try to change the things that can and should be changed.\nDon't be afraic^ to criticize Where all think alike no one\nthinks very much. Democracy gains in strength and wisdom\nfrom the clean criticism and eternal vigilance of its citizens.\nGod Bless America! So say we all. And God bless that\nsymbol of glorious Democracy the loud heckler at the back\nOf the hall even though we may totally disagree with him.\nLet us continue to fight for those things in which we believe,\nalways remembering that it is not the size of the dog ip the fight\nbut the size of the fight in the dog. Let us not be judged by what\nhas been given us in life but rather by the fortitude we bring\ninto it.\nWe live in a nation where opportunities are virtually un\nlimited. Take a man with a strong hand, a pair of overalls, a\nfew ideas and a willingness to work this man can grow big\ndoing big things; or he can grow big doing small things in a\nbetter way.\nBut as Henry Dodd put it: \"The reason many of us do not\nrecognize an opportunity when we meet it is that opportunity\nusually goes around in overalls looking like hard work.\"\nEach of us\u2018becomes the product of his own efforts. Every\nf man writes his own destiny and, as the great Thomas A. Edison\nsaid: \"Everything comes to him who HUSTLES while he WAITS!\"\nYour affairs, even as mine, are but the lengthened shadows\ncast by you and me and those with whom we are associated.\nIf the pattern does not please us, then it is up to us to change it.\nOnly action will change the shape of a shadow. Wishing and\nthinking will not.\nThe pent-up demand for every conceivable kind of mer\nchandise is going to be great during the next few years. We\ncannot complain about the business outlook. But for each of\nus to obtain a share of this business we must roll up our sleeves,\ngrit our teeth and pitch ip there and fight.\nApropos of pitching in the best way in the world to learn\nhow much a fellow has \"on the ball\" is to make the going tough\nfor him. Either he will take it with a grin and come back for\"\nmore or he will fold up. x\nRemember Elbert Hubbard's poem:\nThe tree that never hod to fight\nFor sun and sky and air and light\nThat stood out in the open plain\nAnd always got its share ol rain\nNever became a forest king\nBut lived and died a scrwbby thing.\n\u25a0M tl f\nxnis is equally irue oi men. nna me oniy successiui way\nfor any of us to get along in this world is to take the bit in our\nteeth and solve our own problems. Our hopes and our plans\nmay not necessarily materialize in the manner we desire be\ncause as Jamesl Barrie wrote:\n\"The life of every man is a diary in which he means 1o write one\nstory, and writes another; and his hutiblest hour is when he com\npares that volume as it is with what he vowed to make it.\"\nWe should start NOW to do the things we know we should\ndo. Then we soon would spell \"N O W\" backwards. The best\ntime is to start today the best place right where we are.\nLuck or chance need not rule a man's destiny his fate\ndepends upon his character. If he is strong, he can overcome\ncircumstances; if he is weak, circumstances will overcome him.\nI for one believe in the eternal verities that honest\neffort always wins its reward and that the success of any busi\nness man or individual is assured if the inspiration to succeed\nis never allowed to die. And inspiration will never die unless\nwe lose faith in ourselves.\nThe answer to our reconversion problem and what the\nfuture holds ip store for you and for me is:\nWHAT WILL YOU AND I MAKE IT?\nIT IS ENTIRELY UP TO US! f)\nSincerely,\n\nTito Declares Subasic\nResigned in Move for\nForeign Intervention\nBy the Associated Press.\nLONDON, Oet. 13.\u2014Dr. Ivan Su\nbasic, former Yugoslav foreign min\nister, was accused by Marshal Tito\ntoday of resigning in order to pro\nvide a \u201cmotive for foreign interven\ntion\u201d in Yugoslavia before the elec\ntion scheduled for November 11.\nIn a letter to Subasic, quoted by\nthe Belgrade radio, Tito denied a\ncharge by Subasic that the marshal\u2019s\nagreement with him for a coalition\nregime was not being carried out.\n\"Everything I pledged to do in\nthe agreement with you and every\nthing proposed to us by the Big\nThree in Yalta is being done,\u201d Tito\ndeclared.\nBritish official circles said Su\nbasic\u2019s declaration about Tito\u2019s fail\nure to carry out his agreement and\nthe undemocratic flavor of the elec\ntion plans was well founded, but\nthat there was no British intention\nto intervene.\nTito\u2019s letter made it clear that he\nwas determined to go ahead with\nthe election under present suffrage\nand voting rules.\n\u201cWe shall march firmly and reso\nlutely along the road chosen by all\nour peoples,\u201d the marshal said.\nJohn L. Sullivan\nTo Be Honored by\nAmerican Legion\nAssistant Secretary of the Navy\nJohn L. Sullivan will be presented]\nwith a citation for distinguished\nservice to the American Legion by j\nComdr. Chester A. Bennett at a I\nmeeting of United States Revenue!\nPo6t at 8 p.m. Thursday at Stans\nbury Hall, Georgia and Concord!\navenues.\nMaynard H. Smith, who was!\nawarded the Congressional Medal of\nHonor, will be inducted into the post\nThe department mass installation!\nof officers of 18 posts will be held at!\n3:30 p.m. today at the Sylvan The\nater on the Monument grounds, with;\nDepartment Comdr. Herbert J. Ja-i\ncobi and his staff officiating.\nA concert will be given by the;\nUnited States Navy Band. Admiral\nEmory S. Land, chairman of the\nMaritime Commission will be award-j\ned a citation. All post colors and\nLegionnaires, in uniform or caps, are\nrequested to attend.\nThe department special conven\ntion will be held tomorrow and\nTuesday nights in the auditorium of\nthe Department of Commerce.\nDepartment Comdr. Jacobi and his\ni staff will install officers of Internal\nj Revenue Post Thursday night at\niStansbury Hall and of Bunker Hill\nPost Saturday night at the Legion\nI clubhouse.\nArrangements are being made for,\nthe annual Armistice Day dinner of\nthe Forty and Eight on November 9.\nNational Comdr. Schieberling will be\nthe principal speaker.\nGerald Ryan, chief clerk of the\nCommerce Department, was elected\ncommander of Department of Com-\nmerce Post at the last meeting.\nOther officers are James Brown,\nfirst vice commander; Edward\nGarber, second vice commander;\nEdward Balinger, adjutant; Joseph\nStiegler, ji\\, finance officer; Guy\nCastle, sergeant at arms, and Ben\njamin Reed, chaplain.\nLincoln Post elected the following\nofficers: Commander, Leon B, Lam\nbert; first vice commander, J. A.\nLevin; second vice commander, Ray\nC. Pratt; third vice commander.\nDavid Gordon; sergeant at arms,\nWesley H. Wilson; finance officer,\nE. G. Flester; chaplain, John D.\nGermer; historian, Sidney B. Dia\nmond; past surgeon, Dr. Walter L.\nKline, and trustee for three years,\nHampton D. Percy.\nThey will be installed at the\njoint installation ceremonies today.!\nOfficers of Bunker Hill Unit, to.\n3e installed next Saturday night at\n:he Legion Clubhouse, are as follows\nMrs. Bertha W. Fichthom, presi\nlent; Mrs. Vestra Hocter, Mrs. Heler\nK. Spriggs and Mrs. Ethel L. Booher\n/ice presidents; Mrs. Martha B\nDawson, chaplain; Mrs. Dorothy L\nJohnson, sergeant at arms; Mrs\n\u25a0Cathrine E. Staples, historian; Mrs\nRuth A. Rainey and Mrs. Clealori\nE. Keefer, colorbearers; Mrs, Mil\nired Dodson, secretary; Mrs, Marie\nBurriss, assistant secretary, and\nMrs. Elsie Engel, treasurer.\nUnited States Maritime Unit will\nneet at 2600 Sixteenth street N.W\nit 8:15 am. Tuesday, with Mrs\nMary D. Spence, president, presid\ning.\nThe annual departmental ball will\n3e held December 1 at the Wash\nington Hotel. Mrs. Margaret E\nDarroll is general chairman. Res\nsrvatlons for tables must be made\nwith Mrs. Carroll, Woodley 6532;\nMrs. Marie Totten, Atlantic 7493\n3r Mrs. Lillian Judd, Lincoln 6110\nnot later than November 6.\nThose unable to attend the bal!\nnay send contributions not latei\nthan October 31 to Mrs. Sara!\nDeery, 2431 Newton street N.E.\nInstallation of officers of Victor]\nPost were held last night at the\nLogion clubhouse as follows: H. E\nSweet, commander; J. W. Gulick\n|r., first vice commander; John New\n.oft, second vice commander; E. E\nSmith, third vice commander; H\nH. Silverstein, adjutant; Thomae\n3. McBroom, finance officer; A. N\nSchroeder, chaplain, and C. Wolfe\nsergeant at arms.\nPost colors, donated by the Inde\npendent Taxi Owners\u2019 Association\nwere dedicated.\nAt the last meeting of Georg<\nWashington Post officers were in\nTHE AGE Of\nSUPER-POWER\nIS HERE I\nAcousticon Introduce*\n-,tr\n\u201cs mr\nHEARING AID\nMore hearing power by far\nthan ever thought possible!\nWith Less Battery Voltage!\nLees Weight!\nLess Bulk I\nLess Expense!\nAnnexing new experience for\nhard-of-hearing!\nCall or write today for fret\ndemonstration!\nACOUSTICON ORRISON\n655 Muntey Bid*. NA. 013!\nstalled by Department Comdr. Her\nbert J. Jacobi and his staff in the\nLegion club. Participating in the\nceremonies was the National Guard\nof Honor, Capt. Gail T. Judd, com\nmanding.\nRetiring Comdr. Joseph C. Abrams\nwas commended by Comdr. Jacobi\nfor his accomplishments during the\nyear. At the conclusion of his\naddress he presented past Depart\nment Comdr. Howard S. Fisk, with\na diamond American Legion past\ndepartment commander button.\nCharles L. Schuettler, newly\nelected commander, announced the\nreappointment of Past Comdr\ni __\nJames J. Murphy as adjutant and\nPast Comdr. Lew S. Mohler as\nfinance officer.\nDepartment of Justice Post elected\nthe following officers: Commander,\nArthur Breuer; first vice comman\nder, Curtis Shears; second vice com\nmander, Edward J. Shaughnessy;\nthird vice commander, John P.\nBeebe; adjutant, George Morris Pay;\nfinance officer, William B. Jones;\njudge advocate, Chester A. Prior;\nchaplain, Dr. Daniel C. Buchanan;\nhistorian, David A. Turner; sergeant\nat arms, John Rusen, and color beaijh\ners, Ralph P. Lynch and Francis A.\nPersick.\nThey will be installed at the mass\ninstallation today.\nThe next regular meeting has\nbeen postponed until October 22.\nBMMlWMBIIWWSBIllllMlWWIIIMttlWIIIIliillllllllMtil'a\nTO ALL MY FRIENDS:\nMuch is being said and written about the problems of re\nconversion Can we maintain full employment? And can we\nkeep the industrial machine rolling in high gear?\nWell, former President Franklin D. Roosevelt once observed\n\u2014\"The only thing we have to fear is fear itself!\" How true! And\nhow timely!\nIf the problems of the future appear great, it should be re\nmembered that any job no matter how big can be done if\nsufficient persistence and determination are employed and the\nwillingness exists to pay the price in energy for its accomplish\nment.\nIf one says it cannot be done, it is he who cannot do it. He\nis licked before he starts. And paradoxically, while he is saying\nit can't be done, someone already is doing it! What a lot of\npeople need these days is a good swift kick in the can'ts!\nNo task is particularly difficult if it is divided into small jobs.\nThe experience of difficulty tends to strengthen the mind even as\nphysical labor strengthens the body. We all agree that\nquitters never win but winners never quit.\nIf the elevator to success is not running, then we must climb\nthe stairs. We must never fear failure to the extent that we are\nunwilling to take a chance. Our greatest glory is not in avoiding\nfalls but in rising every time we fall. All of us are entitled to\na quota of mistakes which go to make'us qualify as human\nbeings. A good man does not blame failure but he is absolutely\nmerciless toward lack of effort.\nSo let us keep faith in ourselves. Let us always remember\nthat the future holds nothing for those who have lost faith. Pes\nsimists are never in demand never become leaders.\nTHE LEADER\nH you think you are beaten, you are.\nII you think you dare not. you don\u2019t,\nII you\u2019d like to win. but think you can\u2019t.\nIt\u2019s almost a cinch you won\u2019t.\nIf you think you\u2019ll lose, you re lost\nFor out in the world we find\nSuccess begins with a fellow s will\nIt\u2019s all in the state of mind.\nIf you think you\u2019re outclassed, you are.\nYou\u2019we got to think high to rise;\nYou've got to be sure ol yourself before\nYou ever can win a prize.\nLife's battles don\u2019t always go\nTo the strongest or fastest man\nBut sooner or later the man who wins\nIs the man who thinks he can.\n?A _1_A _ 1___ A _ _A _ \u2019ll _ _ _ A >1 .1\nHof BORDERLINE ANEMIA\nDrawn a Cloud across your Charm?\nBorderline Anemia is robbing\ncountless thousands of their radi\nant good looks their vivacity and\ncharm. Medical records show that\nBorderline Anemia can claim up to\n68% of women as its victims!\nSo, if yod tire quickly \u2014if your\nskin seems to be losing its color and\ntone\u2014watch out! You may have a\nBorderline Anemia resulting fd&m a\nferro-nutritional blood deficiency.\nPuny, Irregular bleed cells\ncause failure ef energy\nBorderline Anemia means that your\nblood cells aren\u2019t big and red enough\nto carry oxygen and release energy to\nevery muscle and fiber. Your blood is\nyour \"supply line\u201d of vigor and vital\nity. Nothing else can take its place!\nIrenlxed Yeast te build\nbleed and energy\nContinuing tiredness, listleSsness and\npallor may, of course be brought\nabout by other conditions. Always\nconsult your physician regularly.\nBut when you have a Borderline\nAnemia, when you find yourself envy\ning 